column1: Add Pinterest HTML Tag to BC
column38:
We are launching a pinterest page for BestColleges. While this may seem like an odd place for our brand there is actually a large thirst for education content on the site. ASO's pinterest got over 40k impressions last month with about a third of the content that BC has. We are hoping this can become a great new source of traffic for BC. 

To verify our website‚Äôs authenticity we need to claim the BC website. When done, our profile picture will show up next to any Pins that come from our site, and a small globe icon will appear to the left of our website‚Äôs URL on our profile. Truly, these just gives our Pinterest Profile more authority and shows we are indeed connected to the BC site.

In order to "claim" our website on Pinterest and prove that we are the owners of the site, we need to add the following HTML tag to BestColleges.com. 

*Below you will find the instructions:*

Add HTML tag
Paste this tag into the <head> section of your site‚Äôs index.html file

<meta name="p:domain_verify" content="b9313302259eb23861402e33b95a201c"/>

column1: SEL ADs showing in place of EXCL ADs in EXCL Ad Blocks
column38: Find examples of AD Blocks promoting SEL schools when we have EXCL coverage.
column101: 12/Mar/19 2:45 PM;dacosta;This issue requires your attention. [~mcomardo]
column102: 12/Mar/19 3:15 PM;dacosta;This issue requires your attention. [~dacosta]
column103: 12/Mar/19 3:15 PM;dacosta;This issue requires your attention. [~jvalencia]
column104:
13/Mar/19 8:34 AM;qm:6fc3e611-5401-48ac-b2fa-b8a969f39e7c:5b106baf93816854030df97a;Just to chime in here, as I chatted with Dave Ashworth offline on this one (specifically the second example with University of the Southwest, so to be fair I did not check the other 2 examples shown) .  In short, there's no technical issue here.  DE is calculated as it was configured to do so, and showing the school/product combos in calculated eRPV order.

What we could improve is how we calculate erpv.  Basically, the bumps don't currently affect the "ML revenue" portion of the formula (that accounts for how much downstream revenue we expect to get in the revenue), but only the expected revenue of the initial school.  We will change this in the next few days, but worth noting that this essentially means that this school was still worth showing in this instance for the ML revenue only.   I firmly do not believe we should artificially bump SEL out of Ad positions if the calculated erpv suggests they should be there.  My 2 cents!

column1: [GoGrad.org] "None" header style needs tweaking (or a new header style needs to be added)
column38:
Right now, GoGrad.org has three header styles available: None, Image Header, and Widget Header.

"None" displays nothing, not even the page's H1. 

"Image Header" displays all inputted header content, but moves everything to the side to accommodate an image.

"Widget" displays all inputted header content and also a widget.

However, we will have plenty of pages where we *do not* want a widget or header image, but we still *do* want to display H1, subheader, and header content. 

Could the "None" option be adjusted to display H1, subhead, and header content?

If not, could we get a new header style added called "Intro Only" or something?

Sample page: https://www.gograd.org/resources/sample-header-page/

07/Feb/19 2:38 PM;syncbot;‚û§ {color:#999999}_Dave Ashworth commented:_{color}

Just took another look at this one. The reason conversions aren't coming into the normalized_events table (and thus, into QV) is that the school in the linkout doesn't match the school noted on the script on the conversion page.

Linkout URL example: https://platform.highereducation.com/editorial-links/collegechoice.net/5126
The school for this one is "New England College - School of Graduate Studies".
The conversion page you eventually land on from that link has "school=new-england-college" in the conversion script parameters. It would need to read "school=new-england-college-school-of-graduate-studies" for the conversion event to match up with the click event.

TL;DR; The school needs to update the conversion script placed on that page to read "school=new-england-college-school-of-graduate-studies".

 !screenshot-1.png|thumbnail! 

https://platform.highereducation.com/mod#eyJ2YWx1ZXMiOnsiZGVncmVlcyI6W10sIm1vbmV0aXphdGlvbnMiOlt7ImlkIjo2LCJuYW1lIjoiU2Nob29sIEJhbm5lcnMiLCJzbHVnIjoic2Nob29sLWJhbm5lcnMifV0sInJvdXRlIjoiaW52ZW50b3J5IiwidXJsIjp7ImlkIjoxMzEsIm5hbWUiOiJ1c25ld3MuY29tIn19fQ==

column103:
22/Jan/19 7:10 AM;dacosta;Adding for future reference:

The issue here was that the affiliate placed the widget sending degree data only.
The MOD rule was expecting the complete DCS, to match it with the rule.
Since it didn't match, it was showing another rule.

So the solution here is:
Ask the affiliate to set the complete DCS.
Or remove completely the degree-data from the placement and set it all via MOD rule.

column38:
Not sure if this is the correct place for this task, but here we go....

Liberty's EXCL LP seems* to be delivering a different [lead_id] value to Liberty than what platform events is capturing internally.  The lead data Liberty is reporting back indicates a [lead_id] with 7 characters but platform events presents a [lead_id] with 9 characters.  It would be helpful to understand what id is currently* being passed along and, assuming the assumptions above are correct, update the id passed to the [lead_id] reported in platform events (example output below with 9 character [lead_id]).

Email string below had Jason Comes on the email string. If further insight is needed, please reach out to Bristol or myself.

Liberty email - "Liberty Lead"

SQL Query:
SELECT *
    FROM prod_platform_events_staging_internal.normalized_events_fact_table_stag
WHERE 
	school_name = 'liberty university online'
    AND year = 2018
    AND month = 12

‚îÜ{color:#707070}Attachments: [Liberty 12.11.2018 (2).xlsx|https://app.asana.com/app/asana/-/get_asset?asset_id=993332853965684] | [SELECT_FROM_prod_platform_events_staging_internal_normalized_eve_201901161458.csv|https://app.asana.com/app/asana/-/get_asset?asset_id=993332853965686]{color}

column103:
17/Jan/19 9:47 AM;syncbot;‚û§ {color:#999999}_Chad Donohue commented:_{color}

We currently do not ingest the _CLICK_ID_ parameter on the Liberty page. So, the `lead_id` reported here will not match up to our data. We would need to add this functionality to grab the parameter once the user lands here and make sure it is sent in the lead payload once the form is submitted.

column38:
I received a notification that our site, TheBestSchools.org, was requesting my location. This has never happened before, and to our knowledge, we are not using geolocation in any of our tools or services (Facebook, etc.)
- I searched for `geolocation` across all the content being called in a page, and the only resource that mentions `geolocation` is this:
> https://thebestschools.org/assets/js/footer.js
- If you view the javascript, you‚Äôll see that there are function calls for an Algolia connectGeoSearch service (also see ngeoSearch and enableGeolocationWithIP)
- Documentation here:
> https://community.algolia.com/instantsearch.js/v2/connectors/connectGeoSearch.html

‚ù± Can you confirm that this is what is prompting a user to approve geo tracking?

‚ù± If this is the cause, since we‚Äôre not using this function of Algolia to build maps, can we turn it off or disable (just this function only‚Äâ‚Äî‚Äâwe want to leave Algolia enabled)?

‚ù± If Algolia is not the cause, can you identify what is, and why it‚Äôs prompting now (i.e., what changed?)?
column101: 09/Jan/19 12:44 PM;dacosta;This issue requires your attention. [~mcomardo]
column102:
09/Jan/19 2:29 PM;dacosta;Hello Rich,

I've been checking this out and I believe it might be an extension on your browser or something you might have installed. We haven't been able to replicate this, and well we don't use location based stuff on any thing.

So could you please let us know what browser/version you are using, to see if we might come up with some possible culprit. Be assured that H-E is not responsible for this request.

Thank you for using Jira!

Becky

column1: EXCL Lead counts not matching up with School Counts
column38:
We are seeing some odd behavior with lead counts in QV. We are seeing examples with TwoU Provider, where schools are actually reporting more leads than clicks. We are also seeing some schools reporting less conversions than we are reporting. I have provided examples of both in screenshots.

https://edudirect.cmn.com/schools/142/profile - School reporting less leads than what is in QV from 12/1 - 12/25


https://edudirect.cmn.com/schools/473/providers/707/caps/1791 - More leads than clicks on 12/25 for this cap bucket in QV.

‚îÜ{color:#707070}Attachments: [image.png|https://app.asana.com/app/asana/-/get_asset?asset_id=956048208738703]{color}
column101: 26/Dec/18 10:24 AM;dacosta;This issue requires your attention. [~mcomardo]
column102: 26/Dec/18 3:10 PM;jvalencia1;*UNC Gillings School of Global Public Health* seems to have repeated tracker pixels. I checked this on metabase and for each registry (or lead) there is another one with the same data (is repeated). I wanted to recreate the issue on different states like New York, South Carolina, Washington (with the VPN) but tracker pixels didn't fire when i filled out and submitted the EXCL forms.
column103:
26/Dec/18 3:33 PM;dacosta;Hello Rich, so Juan and I are both on this task.
SNHU is in fact not adding up any way . Currently I'm troubleshooting the issue with Chad.

Currently the differences are visible between all counts.
 8412 for Admin count
 9803 for SNHU School count
 9836 for Metabase (nomalized_events)
10105 for Metabase(conversion_ledger)
10172 for QV (H-E Count)

So The school is closer to the Metabase(normailized_events) count. 

We'll keep an eye on this and update you as soon as possible.

Becky

column102:
18/Dec/18 8:45 AM;jvalencia1;On Admin we checked out the cap bucket and compared the numbers against the results on metabase. These are the facts we found:
* The Cap Bucket is paused. However, we noticed that a lead was sent today (on Admin) but Metabase doesn't show that registry.
* 8 leads were found between 2018-12-17 and 2018-12-18.
* From those 8, 5 of them have different IP. (There's a lead with 2 entries and another one with 3)
* We filled out the QDFs but trident university wasn't shown because the school is paused.

We will speak with backend team to see how we procedure.

18/Dec/18 9:17 AM;syncbot;‚û§ {color:#999999}_Will Stern commented:_{color}

Yeah, this looks like a bug to me.  My first thought was: ‚Äúdid the last 4+ leads all come in within an hour?‚Äù because caching could potentially cause that to happen and go over by a few.  But that wasn‚Äôt the case - we hit 5 at 8:34am and then the overage in the afternoon.

Thanks,
Becky

column38:
Please remove "Database" from the main site nav and instead nest it under "Online Degrees" at the bottom of that dropdown list. We'd like to rename "Database" to "School Database" once it's nested.

27/Nov/18 7:56 AM;dacosta;Hey Sam, so I checked out the programs and I'm pretty sure I know why they aren't showing up in the EL. Turns out no program snippets are available, and this would cause them to be filtered from the adblocks.

column103:
27/Nov/18 8:59 AM;dacosta;Yeah, it was that. Now Keiser is showing up for Associate's>Medical Assisting. 
So basically if a program has an empty snippet field, it won't be considered for EL. 

Again, these programs will be far down the list because they're SEL, and not starred. After speaking with JLam, MOD rules can't fix SEL programs on an adblock, so if your intention is to make them appear on a site, manual placement might be the only way.

column1: QV reporting conversions but no clicks for a school

column1: Clicks attributed to wrong cap bucket
column38: We have CPC cap buckets grouped by programs for Grand Canyon University. The cap bucket on top has clicks attributed to it from programs not assigned to that cap bucket. column1: Exclusive General lead cap allocation doesn't seem to be working as expected
column38:
My understanding in chatting with Will is that if the DCS of an exclusive lead is unknown, it will assign to the lowest priority eligible cap (eg, still acknowledging publisher/geo restricts).

Looking at Southerner New Hampshire University's cap configuration, , their "LO Assoc." cap bucket is the second highest priority, but it appears that it is receiving the lion's share of the schools "general" leads.

Attaching an image of both the cap configuration where this bucket is 2nd highest priority, and the Oct MTD data extract I've pulled detailing cap distribution of the "unknown" leads for SNHU.
column102:
05/Oct/18 12:46 PM;dacosta;Hello Christian,

This one is tricky. It actually IS working as intended. But while digging to check the issue out I noticed that there is actually an issue with the priority arrangements on Admin. 
There are two priority tabs, one on the School dashboard and another one on the Caps dashboard. So by design, the one on the schools is the one that's being checked for these leads with unknown DCS.
column103:
05/Oct/18 12:49 PM;dacosta;I've attached an image of both priority settings:
 !Different Priority order..png|thumbnail! 
So as you can see on the left side, the LO Assoc. is actually the next in line AFTER skipping the active caps with publisher restrictions.
column104: 05/Oct/18 12:51 PM;dacosta;I will create a separate ticket for backend so that the priorities will sync up on both dashboards, to avoid any confusions and mishaps. Thank you for reporting!

column1: non RN to BSN users seeing RN programs forms 2+
column38:
In reference to:  https://app.asana.com/0/517412949117819/613748271310976/f

I posted there too, but I'll copy below.  For context, in May we worked with Will & team to lower inelgibles in RN to BSN.  The intended functionality should be that users only see this subject if it is their first form OR they already indicated that they have an RN (and are thus eligible for this program).  We should see very few form 2+ ineligibles due to not having a RN liscense.



Posted in Asana: bringing this one back up -- TJ Quinn noticed that we're still seeing a a large number of forms 2+ inelgibles for Select in Rn to BSN (Grand Canyon is most affected, but Chamberlain and Herzing are also relatively affected).  Obviously forms 2+ ineligibles will still be possible to a degree if the user chooses to manually switch the program drop down, but assuming most users don't do that, my understanding is that we shouldn't be seeing this too often.

I submitted a test string and was able to see this (above image):
column101: 24/Sep/18 7:04 PM;dacosta;This issue requires your attention. [~mcomardo]
column102:
25/Sep/18 10:08 AM;dacosta;Ok so I'll post here and on the Asana ticket :

I've been doing some testing and there are a couple of things that aren't working here. 
RNtoBN programs are being presented to high school seniors, both form GCU and Chamberlain (this one requires a grad date even if the user marks they don't have an RN).
Also, in the same funnel the user is being presented with NCU's grad from, so since its a High School senior, all programs appear as invalid.
column103: 25/Sep/18 2:32 PM;dacosta;So i'm gonna merge the two tasks, since the other one has more info. Thank you for using the portal!

31/Aug/18 10:30 AM;dacosta;There are a certain amount of users accepted by each school and when they have reached this limit, they stop showing up in automated ad blocks. On other manually placed adblocks, the schools will continue showing up and accepting users for the specified program, just to continue monetization.

When the link is only for a school, the form will show the available programs. In this case since there are none, the form blocks. Since tomorrow (Sept 1st) all the values will reset, it shouldn't be a problem. However, we will look into this behavior to check if it will be modified. Since August is the most busy month and it is very rare for these schools to reach their limit.

Thank you for reporting!

column1: [Platform] [Web Analytics] - Platform Events often not logging Ref URL for Linkout Prod Views/Conversions
column38:
Apologies if I categorized this wrong, wasn't sure where it went.  This is data related.

Was doing some digging this morning and found that Platform Events (pulling from normalized events table) records a NULL for referring URL about 17% of the time for LINKOUT_PRODUCT_VIEWS & LINKOUT_PRODUCT_CONVERSION event_keys (the WINKOUT view/conversion events appear to be unaffected)

I'll note that this is not a new problem -- appears to be pretty consistent back to the inception of the database.  I'll also note that the long term plan is to use GA for event tracking, but given that we still intend to use this DB for a transactional record, I think it may be worth exploring this issue/addressing if possible.

29/Aug/18 11:52 AM;dacosta;I'll speak with the team on how to approach this issue. Mean while I will set it as deferred, since the service desk has SLAs to meet and I'm not sure how to categorize this one either.

So don't worry, I am working on it, it'll just be in the deferred column while I figure out the workflow. 

I will keep you posted with any update.

column1: [BUG] [EDUDirect] [Platform] [EXCL] Purdue & Liberty EXCL Lead Counts Higher in Admin (QV vs Admin Counts)
column38:
According to Christian Jones, Purdue & Liberty are seeing more leads be recorded in admin than on the school's side.

20/Aug/18 1:26 PM;syncbot;‚û§ {color:#999999}_Jen G commented:_{color}

[Shilpa Shyam](https://app.asana.com/0/231159015628484/list) doesn't have access to Github or Notion, so here are the instructions as they are today:

To remove a school from a page like: https://www.collegedegree.com/courses/business-programs:

  1. Log in to the backend: https://www.collegedegrees.com/admin/domain.php?action=view&id=22.
  2. Select the 'Program Data' tab.
  3. Find the matching program. This can be a wild guess given that many pages have same or similar names.
  4. Click on your guess, and check that the school you want to remove is featured there.
  5. Check "Publish" from yes/on to no/off and Save.
  6. Profit.

column104:
17/Aug/18 7:16 PM;syncbot;‚û§ {color:#999999}_Jen G commented:_{color}

Removing schools from this site is a multi-step process.

I did the first part of this: I flipped the active flag in each of these schools' rows in the database to False.

The next step is where it starts getting tricky. These are all cached, static pages, and they have to be removed from the server so the web application can regenerate them (assuming the web application still works, of course). We don't have a good way to know which files have these schools in them and I don't know how slowly they have to be removed. The instructions say "When deleting the files, be careful that you‚Äôre not giving the web server too many files to generate at once. Use caution when deleting these." Hopefully that just sounds more ominous than it really is. üòÜ

I think this is where we get Matt involved to see how he thinks this could be accomplished and if the web application is likely to run again to regenerate the files.

I'll talk to him on Monday and get his opinion on this.

Thanks!
Jen
column105:
21/Aug/18 10:06 AM;syncbot;‚û§ {color:#999999}_Jen G commented:_{color}

[Shilpa Shyam](https://app.asana.com/0/231159015628484/list): I think we will be able to remove these schools. At least, we will be able to remove pages (that should then be regenerated ü§û) with that exact wording.

There are 16886 unique files with those exact word combinations, so it will take some time to complete the removal since we have to remove them in batches or risk tipping the server over.

Let me know about ITT Tech - that school is all over this site and this is our big opportunity to remove it. I'll remove that if needed and then Matt can begin the process.

Thanks!
Jen

column1: Trident Military Not Showing within multilead
column38:
Moving from a separate email thread to reduce clutter

Attached 2 examples where Trident should have appeared in the multilead if the user marks that they have a military affiliation, as well as my lead string where I passed over them.  This investigation came from seeing that Trident Military was falling far behind their IO for military users (they've only generated a couple leads, should be generating more).  We have had some mixed results with this testing - at one point Trident showed in the multilead last afternoon, but as of this morning I am again not seeing them when submitting test leads.

Hypothesis -- despite being lower priority, their non-military cap bucket may somehow be interfering when it hits its daily cap, causing the military bucket to think it's capped out.

Let me know if you need more information!

Thank you for reporting! I'll get back to you as soon as the issue is identified.
column103:
09/Aug/18 3:37 PM;dacosta;So I'm going to have to escalate this ticket to Will. 
Locally and on Staging, Trident U _is_ being shown. But not on production. 
Multilead seems to be working just fine.  As for the bucket's non-military daily capacity, since the issue isn't being replicated outside of prod, it is hard to change the cap values to determine if it's the culprit.

column1: PIT not functioning as expected (3 cases)
column38:
Been working with Justin and found a few instances where the PIT (and ultimately winkout testing tool) doesn't appear to be showing what it should show (and as far as we can tell, no other restrictions should be coming into play).  This means that we are not serving the school we intend to serve to certain subsets of users.

For all Cases-
Testing on https://platform.highereducation.com/tools/winkouts/winkout-testing-tool
Publisher: BestColleges.com
URL: https://www.bestcolleges.com/features/top-online-schools/

case 1
Degree: Bachelor's
Subject: Business Administration
State: Utah
 
Problem: Should show Southern New Hampshire University as the chosen winkout, but chooses Ashford.  Southern New Hampshire is not restricted for this program, geo or Site.

case 2
Degree: Master's
Subject: Counseling
State: Texas

Problem: Per the rules, should consistently show Capella (the top 2 schools in the most applicable rule are not available).  Instead, this combination coinflips (eg, offers a different school every time)

case 3
Degree: Bachelor's
Subject: Information Technology
State: Texas

Problem: Per the rules, should show Southern New Hampshire, but shows Walden instead. Southern New Hampshire does not even show as an available  winkout, but does not appear to be restricted.

I've been digging and for the Platform WO tool I'm getting these results:

-For Case 1:
 !screenshot-1.png|thumbnail!

-For Case 2:
 !screenshot-2.png|thumbnail! 
I'm indeed getting a coinflip. Walden in this screenshot, but I've also been shown Regent U. For this case Capella U is consistently shown if the URL field is blank.

-For Case 3:

I'm being shown U of Phoenix. However, the rules for this combo seem to conflict.

SNHU is first for Rule 1 vs SNHU is blocked for Rule 2.

I've done other tests with a PIT copy I made mid-June and other combos seem to work fine.
I'd like you to provide more information on how you're testing the cases.
column102:
03/Jul/18 11:05 AM;qm:6fc3e611-5401-48ac-b2fa-b8a969f39e7c:5b106baf93816854030df97a;Hey Dave -- for case 1, Sam, Justin and I are all still getting Ashford.  We're also using the Platform WO tool to test these cases

That case aside, do you then agree that cases 2 & 3 are not functioning as expected?  

Case 2 should not be a coinflip as the rules specify Capella and Walden in the Pin (2 schools pinned above Capella, but neither are available)

And for case 3, agreed that the rules conflict, however our understanding is that only the highest priority (lowest priority value) rule gets evaluated per user -- that is, the block in rule 2 should not even be evaluated as only rule 3 should even be in scope.  Perhaps we're understanding how the PIT rules work differently than how they actually work?

Agreed that the PIT is working in most cases, but I was verifying that some recent changes I implemented a week ago, and when doing so found these 3 scenarios that I could not explain.  Do want to understand if these are functioning incorrectly or if we should be using the tool differently than we are.

attached an image for each of these 3.




!image.png|thumbnail!

!image.png|thumbnail!

!image.png|thumbnail!
column103:
03/Jul/18 11:48 AM;dacosta;So initially - just in case, because it hasn't been mentioned- clear cache for platform and retry case 1, so we can confirm it is showing something different for you (Mitch and Will are also seeing SNHU).

Case 2 is working for Will, but I'm definitely seeing a coinflip - so this is not working as intended.

For case 3, you are right about the lowest priority number prevailing over other rules. However, I spoke with Dave Ashworth and it seems that if a school is blocked in any rule, it's blocked for all rules (this is to avoid having to block the school for every new rule).  So in this case it should show Walden, as it's the second school after SNHU in rule #3. I'm seeing Phoenix, so It isn't working properly either, because the same rules should apply for everyone. 

I'll add Will and Dave to the ticket for any input ,or to point out anything I might have overlooked.

column109:
05/Jul/18 8:29 AM;qm:6fc3e611-5401-48ac-b2fa-b8a969f39e7c:5b106baf93816854030df97a;Dave,

Thanks a ton for your work on this.  I feel a guilty burden now seeing that you sent that at 11PM!  Really appreciate the effort that went into this

Noted that a school block will apply to all users who fit the matching criteria (whether or not the rule is top priority).  Totally makes sense why it is set up that way, I think it just confused us because we were operating under the assumption of "only 1 rule ever applies to a user" -- but we can definitely work with this.

Thanks again Dave & David!
